WEBVTT

1
00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:05.720
Well, if you've got a Bible, please turn to Acts chapter 17.

2
00:00:05.720 --> 00:00:08.380
Here just a little bit I'll have Ethan come in and read it.

3
00:00:08.380 --> 00:00:11.840
Just to share with you what we're doing at the moment.

4
00:00:11.840 --> 00:00:18.840
We're starting a new series here called Firm Foundation, What We Believe and Why It Matters.

5
00:00:18.840 --> 00:00:24.200
And last week we looked at the fact that Jesus is building his church.

6
00:00:24.200 --> 00:00:28.600
And he's building his church on a rock on a firm foundation.

7
00:00:28.600 --> 00:00:30.120
So what is that rock?

8
00:00:30.120 --> 00:00:35.600
Well Ephesians chapter 2 and verse 20 speaks of Jesus as being the chief cornerstone, but

9
00:00:35.600 --> 00:00:40.960
it also talks about God building his church on the apostles and prophets.

10
00:00:40.960 --> 00:00:45.360
So Christ is the foundation of the church, but he's also, he's made known to us through

11
00:00:45.360 --> 00:00:52.440
the teaching of the apostles and prophets, which we have here for us in the Word of God,

12
00:00:52.440 --> 00:00:56.000
which centers on the person and work of Jesus.

13
00:00:56.000 --> 00:01:00.000
So as Trinity Fellowship begins, you know, as this new church plant, we want to be built

14
00:01:00.000 --> 00:01:04.600
together on the same foundation, on the firm foundation of the scriptures.

15
00:01:04.600 --> 00:01:07.120
We want to be built in the foundation of Christ.

16
00:01:07.120 --> 00:01:11.840
So throughout the fall, both on Sundays but also in home groups, we're going to be

17
00:01:11.840 --> 00:01:15.560
working through our statement of faith as a church, just so we all know what it

18
00:01:15.560 --> 00:01:17.200
says together.

19
00:01:17.200 --> 00:01:20.160
And there are some foundational truths, I think it's nine foundational truths

20
00:01:20.160 --> 00:01:22.600
that we find in our statement of faith.

21
00:01:22.720 --> 00:01:26.400
And we'll come to a different portion of scripture each week where we see that

22
00:01:26.400 --> 00:01:28.640
doctrine being taught.

23
00:01:28.640 --> 00:01:32.480
And each week we're going to read part of our statement of faith, this part that

24
00:01:32.480 --> 00:01:33.080
we're covering.

25
00:01:33.080 --> 00:01:37.200
So if you would look on your worship guide, I'm just going to read it.

26
00:01:37.200 --> 00:01:39.000
We're not going to read it together like we did earlier.

27
00:01:39.000 --> 00:01:42.600
We see our statement of faith, what it says on God.

28
00:01:42.600 --> 00:01:45.440
So you'll see that there at the bottom.

29
00:01:45.440 --> 00:01:50.520
It says, we believe in one God, creator and sustainer of all things,

30
00:01:50.520 --> 00:01:57.480
sovereign and supreme, existing eternally as three persons, father, son, and

31
00:01:57.480 --> 00:02:02.360
Holy Spirit, with each person being fully God.

32
00:02:02.360 --> 00:02:04.040
So why do we believe this about God?

33
00:02:04.040 --> 00:02:06.400
Why does it matter?

34
00:02:06.400 --> 00:02:09.640
Well, that's what we see in Acts chapter 17.

35
00:02:09.640 --> 00:02:12.640
So Ethan, if you could come and read that for us, I would appreciate it.

36
00:02:12.640 --> 00:02:13.720
Thank you.

37
00:02:13.720 --> 00:02:18.000
Acts chapter 17 verse 16 through 34.

38
00:02:18.000 --> 00:02:23.840
Now while Paul was waiting for them at Athens, his spirit was provoked within him

39
00:02:23.840 --> 00:02:27.120
as he saw that the city was full of idols.

40
00:02:27.120 --> 00:02:31.480
So he reasoned in the synagogue with the Jews and the devout persons and

41
00:02:31.480 --> 00:02:35.200
in the marketplace every day with those who happened to be there.

42
00:02:35.200 --> 00:02:40.640
Some of the Epicurean and Stoic philosophers also converse with him.

43
00:02:40.640 --> 00:02:44.600
And some said, what does this babbler wish to say?

44
00:02:44.640 --> 00:02:50.160
Others said, he seems to be a preacher of foreign divinities because he was preaching

45
00:02:50.160 --> 00:02:52.560
Jesus and the resurrection.

46
00:02:52.560 --> 00:02:59.480
And they took him and brought him to the Aeropagus saying, may we know that this new

47
00:02:59.480 --> 00:03:04.600
teaching is that you are presenting or you bring some strange things to our ears.

48
00:03:04.600 --> 00:03:08.080
We wish to know therefore what these things mean.

49
00:03:08.080 --> 00:03:12.800
Now all the Athenians and the foreigners who live there would spend their time in

50
00:03:12.800 --> 00:03:16.720
nothing except telling or hearing something new.

51
00:03:16.720 --> 00:03:17.920
Verse 22.

52
00:03:17.920 --> 00:03:24.440
So Paul standing in the midst of the Aeropagus said, men of Athens, I perceive that in every

53
00:03:24.440 --> 00:03:27.040
way you are very religious.

54
00:03:27.040 --> 00:03:33.000
For as I passed along and observed the objects of your worship, I found also an altar with

55
00:03:33.000 --> 00:03:36.760
this inscription to the unknown God.

56
00:03:36.760 --> 00:03:41.240
What therefore you worship as unknown this I proclaimed to you.

57
00:03:41.240 --> 00:03:46.320
The God who made the world and everything in it being Lord of heaven and earth does not

58
00:03:46.320 --> 00:03:53.880
live in temples made by man, nor is he served by human hands as though he needed anything,

59
00:03:53.880 --> 00:03:58.560
since he himself gives to all mankind life and breath and everything.

60
00:03:58.560 --> 00:04:03.120
And he made from one man every nation of mankind to live on all the face of the

61
00:04:03.120 --> 00:04:08.840
earth, having determined allotted periods in the boundaries of their dwelling place,

62
00:04:08.840 --> 00:04:13.600
that they should seek God and perhaps feel their way toward him and find him.

63
00:04:13.600 --> 00:04:19.960
Yet he is actually not far from each one of us, for in him we live and move and have

64
00:04:19.960 --> 00:04:27.240
our being, as even some of your own poets have said, for we are indeed his offspring.

65
00:04:27.240 --> 00:04:32.040
Being then God's offspring, we ought not to think that the divine being is like gold

66
00:04:32.040 --> 00:04:37.920
or silver or stone, an image formed by the art and imagination of man.

67
00:04:37.920 --> 00:04:43.440
In times of ignorance God overlooked, but now he commands all people everywhere to

68
00:04:43.440 --> 00:04:48.080
repent, because he has fixed a day on which he will judge the world in

69
00:04:48.080 --> 00:04:53.200
righteousness by a man whom he has appointed, and of this he has given

70
00:04:53.200 --> 00:04:57.040
assurance to all by raising him from the dead.

71
00:04:57.040 --> 00:05:02.120
Now when they heard of the resurrection of the dead, some mocked, but others said,

72
00:05:02.120 --> 00:05:05.040
we will hear you again about this.

73
00:05:05.040 --> 00:05:09.920
So Paul went out from their midst, but some men joined him and believed,

74
00:05:09.920 --> 00:05:17.440
among whom also were Dionysius, the Aropagite, and a woman named Demirus,

75
00:05:17.440 --> 00:05:19.040
and others with them.

76
00:05:19.040 --> 00:05:20.680
This is the word of the Lord.

77
00:05:20.680 --> 00:05:21.680
Thanks be to God.

78
00:05:21.680 --> 00:05:26.680
Let's pray together shall we.

79
00:05:26.680 --> 00:05:31.080
The grass withers and the flower fades, but Lord your word stands forever.

80
00:05:31.840 --> 00:05:35.320
So I pray that by your grace you would show us the truth of your word,

81
00:05:35.320 --> 00:05:39.320
and we pray that you would take our lives and build them together upon it.

82
00:05:39.320 --> 00:05:42.000
We ask all this in your name and for your glory.

83
00:05:42.000 --> 00:05:44.000
Amen.

84
00:05:44.000 --> 00:05:49.160
Well, the first time I ever traveled to the UK, I was with a couple of friends,

85
00:05:49.160 --> 00:05:54.040
and we wanted to, we had 48 hours in London roughly, and so we wanted to

86
00:05:54.040 --> 00:05:57.800
see as much of London as we could, so we kind of got on the back of,

87
00:05:57.800 --> 00:06:00.520
or the top of one of these double-decker buses we can see out across,

88
00:06:00.520 --> 00:06:01.680
and they take you to major sites.

89
00:06:01.680 --> 00:06:03.560
We saw like Buckingham Palace.

90
00:06:03.560 --> 00:06:08.560
We saw Big Bend, places like that, but also had another place I wanted to go to

91
00:06:08.560 --> 00:06:10.800
that I heard about called Speakers Corner.

92
00:06:10.800 --> 00:06:12.920
Has anybody heard of Speakers Corner before?

93
00:06:12.920 --> 00:06:14.960
It's a fascinating place.

94
00:06:14.960 --> 00:06:17.840
So it's in Central London.

95
00:06:17.840 --> 00:06:21.600
It's in Hyde Park, and it's basically an area that people go to.

96
00:06:21.600 --> 00:06:24.280
It's kind of an area where free speech is championed,

97
00:06:24.280 --> 00:06:28.200
and people will go and give speeches or hold debates about all kinds of different things.

98
00:06:28.240 --> 00:06:32.040
So you have, like, say, Muslim apologists who would be there kind of,

99
00:06:32.040 --> 00:06:37.240
you know, talking about Islam, and then over here you'd have somebody talking about socialism,

100
00:06:37.240 --> 00:06:41.960
and then over here you would have somebody talking about alien abduction,

101
00:06:41.960 --> 00:06:46.200
and why their story is true, and you'd have all of these different people

102
00:06:46.200 --> 00:06:48.920
sharing all these different beliefs about all these different things,

103
00:06:48.920 --> 00:06:52.520
and as we walked up, it was on a Sunday, and we had just been to a church,

104
00:06:52.520 --> 00:06:56.120
and we were walking up holding our Bibles, and we were just immediately,

105
00:06:56.120 --> 00:06:58.600
like, sworn by people wanting to debate with us,

106
00:06:58.600 --> 00:07:01.320
you know, thinking that we were there as Christians ready to debate,

107
00:07:01.320 --> 00:07:04.840
and so we ended up, you know, these Orthodox Jews specifically came up

108
00:07:04.840 --> 00:07:08.760
and wanted to have a debate with us about whether or not Jesus was the Messiah,

109
00:07:08.760 --> 00:07:11.000
and they were ready for it.

110
00:07:11.000 --> 00:07:15.760
But as I walked up, I remember seeing all of these different people going there

111
00:07:15.760 --> 00:07:18.640
to hear about all these different new things or different ideas,

112
00:07:18.640 --> 00:07:24.320
and thinking, this is just like Acts 17, what we read there,

113
00:07:24.360 --> 00:07:30.440
because Paul has gone to the city of Athens, and Athens was the kind of intellectual

114
00:07:30.440 --> 00:07:33.920
and cultural capital of ancient Greece.

115
00:07:33.920 --> 00:07:38.320
It was a hub for philosophy, architecture, the arts.

116
00:07:38.320 --> 00:07:42.400
It was also a place that was rampant with idolatry,

117
00:07:42.400 --> 00:07:45.000
and people were sharing all of their different ideas,

118
00:07:45.000 --> 00:07:49.600
but one of the things that you could see was the idols that people were worshiping.

119
00:07:49.600 --> 00:07:55.520
One Roman author wrote that it was easier to find a God in Athens than a man.

120
00:07:55.520 --> 00:08:03.080
It was home to many thousands of images, statues, shrines of all these different gods,

121
00:08:03.080 --> 00:08:08.240
and many of them were formed by some of the greatest sculptors that have ever lived,

122
00:08:08.240 --> 00:08:12.600
and some of these can still be seen in museums today.

123
00:08:12.600 --> 00:08:20.200
But Paul, instead of being enamored by their beauty, was appalled by their blasphemy.

124
00:08:20.200 --> 00:08:24.680
So as he saw all of these different idols everywhere, he was appalled.

125
00:08:24.680 --> 00:08:29.680
His spirit was provoked within him, you see there in verse 16.

126
00:08:29.680 --> 00:08:36.480
The word provoked can carry the idea of being irritated or stirred up even to the point of anger.

127
00:08:36.480 --> 00:08:41.920
So Paul is stirred up, interestingly, the Greek translation of the Old Testament

128
00:08:41.920 --> 00:08:47.120
that was being used at that time used the same word to speak about the jealousy,

129
00:08:47.120 --> 00:08:53.040
the righteous jealousy of God when people worshiped idols.

130
00:08:53.040 --> 00:08:56.960
So you read about that in Isaiah 65 or Hosea 8.

131
00:08:56.960 --> 00:09:03.080
You see Yahweh alone is God, and he should be worshiped alone as God.

132
00:09:03.080 --> 00:09:06.400
And since Paul knows the Lord and has a close walk with him,

133
00:09:06.400 --> 00:09:13.280
it's no surprise that he is so disturbed as he sees all of these idols in the city of Athens.

134
00:09:13.280 --> 00:09:18.200
So while he's stirred up about the idolatry, even angered,

135
00:09:18.200 --> 00:09:24.440
it's clear that he has a heart for the people who are worshiping these idols.

136
00:09:24.440 --> 00:09:26.120
He sees that they're enslaved by them.

137
00:09:26.120 --> 00:09:27.960
He wants them to be set free.

138
00:09:27.960 --> 00:09:33.880
And so he deals with the idolatry of the city, not with a sledgehammer kind of going to town.

139
00:09:33.880 --> 00:09:36.680
He deals with it through speech.

140
00:09:36.680 --> 00:09:37.960
He speaks to them.

141
00:09:37.960 --> 00:09:39.440
He speaks up.

142
00:09:39.440 --> 00:09:42.560
We read about how he first speaks to the Jews and the synagogue,

143
00:09:42.560 --> 00:09:46.480
but then he then takes his message to the marketplace.

144
00:09:46.480 --> 00:09:52.200
And when it says marketplace, we might think like a Walmart or a farmer's market or things like that.

145
00:09:52.200 --> 00:09:58.160
But when it, the kind of marketplace it's talking about here is more of like a marketplace of ideas.

146
00:09:58.160 --> 00:10:04.880
Right? So think Speaker's Corner or think maybe a, you know, a debate on a college campus,

147
00:10:04.880 --> 00:10:10.760
things like that where there's this kind of public forum of ideas that are being shared and debated.

148
00:10:10.760 --> 00:10:17.440
And Paul encounters all sorts when he enters this marketplace of ideas and begins speaking about God.

149
00:10:17.440 --> 00:10:24.840
He encounters in verse 18 the Epicureans who to oversimplify were presuming a life of pleasure.

150
00:10:24.840 --> 00:10:33.440
He encounters the Stoics who once again to oversimplify were presuming a life of self-discipline and meaning through that.

151
00:10:33.440 --> 00:10:38.160
And then you just had your average Athenians who were there seeing what was happening and having discussions.

152
00:10:38.160 --> 00:10:46.080
We read that they were there to tell or hear about something new as part of the culture in that area.

153
00:10:46.080 --> 00:10:51.960
You know, the spirit of Athens is still alive and well today.

154
00:10:52.080 --> 00:10:57.320
And it's available to stream on whatever podcast platform you use.

155
00:10:57.320 --> 00:11:03.760
I mean, when you think about all the information that we have available to us today and all the ideas that get conveyed through that,

156
00:11:03.760 --> 00:11:11.640
all of the idolatry and the gods and philosophies of Athens pales in comparison to all of the ideas that are floating around

157
00:11:11.640 --> 00:11:19.440
and the next new thing that everybody's listening to and engaging with in the age of the Internet.

158
00:11:19.440 --> 00:11:24.200
The fact is the people of Athens and the people of our day don't need to hear just some new thing.

159
00:11:24.200 --> 00:11:34.560
They need a new life and that life is found in the true and living God who has made himself known to us in Jesus.

160
00:11:34.560 --> 00:11:35.880
So this is what Paul preaches.

161
00:11:35.880 --> 00:11:41.960
We're told that he preaches Jesus and the resurrection in verse 18 among these people.

162
00:11:41.960 --> 00:11:44.560
That's what he comes preaching.

163
00:11:44.560 --> 00:11:46.640
And he receives a mixed reaction.

164
00:11:46.640 --> 00:11:48.840
But at least the door is still open for him to share more.

165
00:11:48.840 --> 00:11:52.160
He's invited to what's called the Areopagus.

166
00:11:52.160 --> 00:11:54.160
Now, the Areopagus was a literal place.

167
00:11:54.160 --> 00:11:59.960
I mean, it's translated Mars Hill, like the God of Mars, the God of war in this hill is this outcrop of rock.

168
00:11:59.960 --> 00:12:03.160
We had all of these idols there.

169
00:12:03.160 --> 00:12:07.320
But you also had a council that was referred to as the Areopagus.

170
00:12:07.320 --> 00:12:12.640
And they were the kind of gatekeepers that determined what gods would be allowed into the city.

171
00:12:12.640 --> 00:12:18.800
Now, there are all these different gods, but you had to have this kind of council in place that was testing whether or not

172
00:12:18.800 --> 00:12:22.000
you'd be allowed to preach this new God that you were bringing into town.

173
00:12:22.000 --> 00:12:31.160
So when Paul comes preaching Jesus and the resurrection, he's then brought before this council to share before them.

174
00:12:31.160 --> 00:12:35.640
And the sermon that he preaches, I mean, it is masterful.

175
00:12:35.640 --> 00:12:40.560
It is both bold but also skillfully subversive.

176
00:12:40.560 --> 00:12:44.600
And there's something to learn when it comes to proclaiming the gospel.

177
00:12:44.600 --> 00:12:48.440
So he both connects with his audience as well as confronting them.

178
00:12:48.480 --> 00:12:53.280
So he connects with them entering into their worldview.

179
00:12:53.280 --> 00:12:58.080
He finds points of agreement and he says, like, for example, they have this altar to the unknown God.

180
00:12:58.080 --> 00:13:02.720
And he said, well, this God that you're worshiping that's unknown, he's the one I'm going to declare to you.

181
00:13:02.720 --> 00:13:05.320
So they're listening.

182
00:13:05.320 --> 00:13:11.840
He quotes some of their poets instead of just kind of talking about the authority of Scripture from people who've never engaged with the Scripture before.

183
00:13:11.840 --> 00:13:13.960
He engages with their authorities.

184
00:13:13.960 --> 00:13:16.120
So he's connecting with them.

185
00:13:16.120 --> 00:13:19.080
But then he's also confronting him.

186
00:13:19.080 --> 00:13:26.760
He's showing the inconsistencies and inadequacies of their worldview and showing them that the life that they were made for,

187
00:13:26.760 --> 00:13:31.560
that they're hungry for, can only be found in the true and living God.

188
00:13:31.560 --> 00:13:38.080
And he contrasts the God that he speaks about, the God who's revealed himself to us in Scripture and in Jesus,

189
00:13:38.080 --> 00:13:42.440
with the idolatry that they were involved in.

190
00:13:44.320 --> 00:13:47.480
The world is still filled with idolatry today.

191
00:13:47.480 --> 00:13:54.600
You know, we live in a pluralistic society that worships and serves all kinds of things that are not God.

192
00:13:54.600 --> 00:14:00.240
Whether it be pleasure or power or possessions, we could go on.

193
00:14:00.240 --> 00:14:07.240
And what these gods offer to us, so to speak, is nothing compared to the true and living God.

194
00:14:07.240 --> 00:14:11.120
So how can we know the true God?

195
00:14:11.160 --> 00:14:12.160
What is he like?

196
00:14:12.160 --> 00:14:15.720
And how is he different to the gods of this world?

197
00:14:15.720 --> 00:14:25.800
You see, God cannot be known through human philosophy or through art and imagination and idolatry.

198
00:14:25.800 --> 00:14:32.720
Now there may be echoes of him found there within all of those things, like Paul pointing to the unknown God.

199
00:14:32.720 --> 00:14:36.840
But those things cannot show us who he truly is.

200
00:14:36.840 --> 00:14:44.040
And here we see that the unknown God is made known to us through the preaching of the Word.

201
00:14:44.040 --> 00:14:48.480
The unknown God is made known through the preaching of the Word.

202
00:14:48.480 --> 00:14:51.920
He is revealed when the message is proclaimed.

203
00:14:51.920 --> 00:14:55.920
So Paul, like we said, he doesn't reference specific Bible passages here.

204
00:14:55.920 --> 00:14:57.920
You can read about his sermons and synagogues.

205
00:14:57.920 --> 00:15:01.840
He would be going from one Scripture to another, showing that Jesus is the Christ.

206
00:15:01.840 --> 00:15:09.680
But in this audience, while he doesn't explicitly mention Scripture, everything that he says is Scriptural.

207
00:15:09.680 --> 00:15:16.080
So God is revealing himself through the proclamation of his Word here.

208
00:15:16.080 --> 00:15:18.080
So what is this God like?

209
00:15:18.080 --> 00:15:20.960
Well, Paul doesn't say everything he could say here.

210
00:15:20.960 --> 00:15:29.280
And what we have recorded for us is I don't think the totality of what Paul was saying here is summaries of what he was preaching in these places.

211
00:15:29.280 --> 00:15:35.720
For example, you know, I saw our statement of faith that we read just a moment ago, speaks of God as Trinity, Father, Son, and Holy Spirit.

212
00:15:35.720 --> 00:15:40.800
And certainly Paul is proclaiming the Father and he then ends with proclaiming the Son.

213
00:15:40.800 --> 00:15:48.440
And when you look at it in light of the whole book of Acts, Acts chapter one and verse eight, sets the scene, says that he's proclaiming the Gospel by the power of the Spirit.

214
00:15:48.440 --> 00:15:50.080
So the Trinity is present.

215
00:15:50.080 --> 00:15:51.800
But that's not what he's kind of drawing out here.

216
00:15:51.800 --> 00:15:53.440
So we don't have everything.

217
00:15:53.440 --> 00:15:57.560
Here we see that God is greater than the so-called gods of the world.

218
00:15:57.560 --> 00:16:02.560
And what I'm going to do, you can, when we say, like, OK, what does this passage teach us about God?

219
00:16:02.560 --> 00:16:04.760
What does this sermon tell us about God?

220
00:16:04.760 --> 00:16:06.560
There's about 10 things.

221
00:16:06.560 --> 00:16:09.320
So I've managed to get it down to about seven.

222
00:16:09.320 --> 00:16:10.240
OK.

223
00:16:10.240 --> 00:16:12.360
And and we're in your thing.

224
00:16:12.360 --> 00:16:14.440
Oh, no, how long are we going to be here?

225
00:16:14.440 --> 00:16:16.240
The oven's on at home.

226
00:16:16.240 --> 00:16:25.080
We're going to go just rapid fire and say, OK, what are what are these seven or more things that Paul tells us about God here?

227
00:16:25.080 --> 00:16:25.520
OK.

228
00:16:25.520 --> 00:16:27.360
And then how are we responding to this God?

229
00:16:27.360 --> 00:16:30.760
So first of all, we see that God is Creator.

230
00:16:30.760 --> 00:16:35.600
So Paul begins his sermon saying.

231
00:16:35.600 --> 00:16:45.000
Verse 24, the God who made the world and everything in it being Lord of heaven and earth does not live in temples made by man.

232
00:16:45.000 --> 00:16:45.640
So stop there.

233
00:16:45.640 --> 00:16:48.160
So he begins with God as Creator.

234
00:16:48.160 --> 00:16:50.640
He is the Creator of all things.

235
00:16:50.640 --> 00:16:56.720
So I've got friends who've moved to a tribe in Papua New Guinea.

236
00:16:56.760 --> 00:17:00.840
And this this tribe had never heard of the Christian scriptures, never heard of Jesus.

237
00:17:00.840 --> 00:17:02.720
So they didn't just go straight into the gospel.

238
00:17:02.720 --> 00:17:05.800
They had to go right back to there's a God and he is the Creator.

239
00:17:05.800 --> 00:17:07.160
So this is where Paul begins here.

240
00:17:07.160 --> 00:17:08.120
There's a Creator God.

241
00:17:08.120 --> 00:17:09.880
He created all things.

242
00:17:09.880 --> 00:17:15.800
And in this, we see that God exists above and outside of his creation.

243
00:17:15.800 --> 00:17:20.120
So there is a distinction between the Creator and that which is created.

244
00:17:20.120 --> 00:17:26.320
And those things which are created must never be worshiped and served as God as the Creator.

245
00:17:26.320 --> 00:17:28.920
There must be a clear distinction there.

246
00:17:28.920 --> 00:17:31.240
And by the way, you look at like 1 Corinthians 8.

247
00:17:31.240 --> 00:17:34.680
If you entertain whether or not these gods are actually gods.

248
00:17:34.680 --> 00:17:38.320
1 Corinthians 8, 4 says they're not God at all.

249
00:17:38.320 --> 00:17:39.520
These are not gods at all.

250
00:17:39.520 --> 00:17:41.800
They're so called gods.

251
00:17:41.800 --> 00:17:53.520
And Paul points out, for example, how ludicrous it is to think that the God who created everything could somehow be contained in temples made, created by human hands.

252
00:17:53.600 --> 00:18:01.280
This is a pretty bold move for Paul to make while he's literally standing like in this center of idol worship surrounded by all these temples.

253
00:18:01.280 --> 00:18:06.800
He says God doesn't dwell in temples made by human hands, but they keep listening.

254
00:18:06.800 --> 00:18:14.520
You see, God cannot be domesticated and brought down to a place where he can be managed by his creatures.

255
00:18:14.520 --> 00:18:21.600
And that includes our own conception of God, like creating a God that makes sense to us.

256
00:18:21.600 --> 00:18:23.520
He's not going to be contained in that.

257
00:18:23.520 --> 00:18:29.800
Creation is not God, but it is a theater revealing the glory of God.

258
00:18:29.800 --> 00:18:36.520
So whether or not you've ever cracked open a Bible and read Genesis 1.1, in the beginning, God created the heavens and the earth.

259
00:18:36.520 --> 00:18:45.680
You are surrounded by the revelation of his existence and his power and his beauty in creation.

260
00:18:45.680 --> 00:18:46.680
We can't escape it.

261
00:18:46.680 --> 00:18:49.880
We might choose to ignore it, but we cannot escape it.

262
00:18:49.880 --> 00:18:56.960
One Christian in a country where the church was being persecuted said, you can pull down our steeples, but you cannot pull down the stars.

263
00:18:56.960 --> 00:18:59.160
Whereas God isn't just revealed in a church.

264
00:18:59.160 --> 00:19:02.640
He's revealed in creation as well.

265
00:19:02.640 --> 00:19:05.000
So he's creator, but he's also sustainer.

266
00:19:05.000 --> 00:19:06.240
So let's read what it says next.

267
00:19:06.240 --> 00:19:18.360
He says, nor is he served by human hands as though he needed anything, since he himself gives to all mankind life and breath and everything.

268
00:19:18.360 --> 00:19:22.720
So God didn't just create everything in the beginning and then just kind of leave it to run its course.

269
00:19:22.720 --> 00:19:24.680
Like I've got one of those little spinning tops in mind.

270
00:19:24.680 --> 00:19:28.600
Like he kind of started it off and then just left it to go.

271
00:19:28.600 --> 00:19:32.480
No, he sustains all things.

272
00:19:32.480 --> 00:19:41.800
So Jesus said it this way in Matthew 5, he causes the sun to rise on the just and the unjust.

273
00:19:41.800 --> 00:19:42.800
All right?

274
00:19:42.800 --> 00:19:46.440
He gives rain as well.

275
00:19:46.440 --> 00:19:47.920
Hebrews 1.3.

276
00:19:47.960 --> 00:19:53.360
He upholds all things right now by the word of his power.

277
00:19:53.360 --> 00:19:59.200
Colossians 1.17 talks about how in Jesus everything is held together.

278
00:19:59.200 --> 00:20:06.400
So while God is distinct from his creation, he's actively involved in creation, sustaining it, keeping it going.

279
00:20:06.400 --> 00:20:08.560
And that includes us.

280
00:20:08.560 --> 00:20:10.360
He's the one who gives us life.

281
00:20:10.360 --> 00:20:14.160
He's the one who gives us breath and everything that we need to live in the world.

282
00:20:14.160 --> 00:20:20.160
When you breathe in, you're breathing in the oxygen that he has provided.

283
00:20:20.160 --> 00:20:22.640
He's present and active right now.

284
00:20:22.640 --> 00:20:24.960
And idolatry flips this around.

285
00:20:24.960 --> 00:20:31.040
You got gods who are needy, created by us, needed to be sustained by us.

286
00:20:31.040 --> 00:20:35.120
As I was thinking about this, I started thinking about that craze that took place in the 90s.

287
00:20:35.120 --> 00:20:40.560
For those of you who are old enough to remember about gigapets and Tamagotchi's, did any of you ever get sucked into that?

288
00:20:40.560 --> 00:20:43.000
I got pulled into that craze.

289
00:20:43.000 --> 00:20:44.280
It was horrible.

290
00:20:44.280 --> 00:20:46.120
They were these kind of, how would you describe it?

291
00:20:46.120 --> 00:20:50.120
Like a little virtual pet that would be on a key chain and you had to keep it fed.

292
00:20:50.120 --> 00:20:53.080
You had to keep it watered, make sure you had enough sleep and all the rest.

293
00:20:53.080 --> 00:20:57.240
And it would just constantly make noise to kind of get your attention.

294
00:20:57.240 --> 00:21:00.520
And I remember just getting fed up and just like slinging mine across the room.

295
00:21:00.520 --> 00:21:03.400
It was just too needy for me.

296
00:21:03.400 --> 00:21:04.120
All right.

297
00:21:04.120 --> 00:21:06.840
God is not needy, right?

298
00:21:06.840 --> 00:21:09.320
So Paul's surrounded by all these needy idols.

299
00:21:09.320 --> 00:21:10.920
He said, God is not needy.

300
00:21:10.920 --> 00:21:15.240
He is not dependent upon us for anything.

301
00:21:15.240 --> 00:21:18.920
We are dependent upon Him for everything.

302
00:21:18.920 --> 00:21:21.240
You could really make another point about God.

303
00:21:21.240 --> 00:21:24.440
This is that He is self-existent.

304
00:21:24.440 --> 00:21:33.640
He reveals Himself to Moses as the I am, whose existence is in no way contingent upon anything outside of Himself.

305
00:21:33.640 --> 00:21:36.680
He is.

306
00:21:36.680 --> 00:21:38.840
We are entirely dependent upon Him.

307
00:21:38.840 --> 00:21:39.880
And He's so gracious.

308
00:21:39.880 --> 00:21:40.840
There's another point for you.

309
00:21:40.840 --> 00:21:44.360
He provides for His creatures.

310
00:21:44.360 --> 00:21:46.760
And this should humble us and cause us to praise Him.

311
00:21:46.760 --> 00:21:47.000
All right.

312
00:21:47.000 --> 00:21:50.280
So He's Creator, Sustainer, but He's also ruler.

313
00:21:50.280 --> 00:21:51.080
He's the ruler.

314
00:21:51.080 --> 00:21:55.880
So if He created all things, then He's the ruler of all as well.

315
00:21:55.880 --> 00:22:01.880
So Greeks believed in these separate gods who ruled over different domains of creation.

316
00:22:01.880 --> 00:22:09.400
So you've got the God of the sky, Zeus, or the sea, Poseidon, or the underworld, Hades.

317
00:22:09.400 --> 00:22:11.000
This could go on.

318
00:22:11.000 --> 00:22:17.400
So when Paul asserts that God created the world and everything in it, in the context he's proclaiming that in,

319
00:22:17.400 --> 00:22:21.240
he's asserting that there is one God who reigns over all.

320
00:22:21.240 --> 00:22:26.840
And that includes not only the natural world, but also humanity and the nations of the world.

321
00:22:26.840 --> 00:22:28.920
So go on to verse 26.

322
00:22:28.920 --> 00:22:29.400
He says,

323
00:22:40.280 --> 00:22:43.560
So God rules over humanity because He created humanity.

324
00:22:44.360 --> 00:22:47.880
He speaks here both of the unity and diversity of humanity.

325
00:22:47.880 --> 00:22:49.240
That is by design.

326
00:22:50.040 --> 00:22:54.040
So the unity of humanity, spoken of here in the sense that God created us from this one

327
00:22:54.040 --> 00:22:55.400
common ancestor, Adam.

328
00:22:56.040 --> 00:23:00.920
So we all share this humanity as image bearers of God.

329
00:23:01.880 --> 00:23:04.040
But also speaks of the diversity of humanity.

330
00:23:04.040 --> 00:23:06.200
God created us with diversity in view.

331
00:23:06.200 --> 00:23:09.000
He creates the different nations or ethnicities.

332
00:23:09.720 --> 00:23:15.320
We'll look more at that in a couple of weeks when we look at humanity as the subject of the day.

333
00:23:16.040 --> 00:23:18.120
We see that God not only rules over humanity though.

334
00:23:18.120 --> 00:23:19.400
He rules over history.

335
00:23:19.960 --> 00:23:23.320
So people's nations and borders have come and gone.

336
00:23:23.320 --> 00:23:27.240
And God stands sovereign over them all.

337
00:23:27.240 --> 00:23:32.120
He determines their allotted periods and the boundaries of their dwelling place.

338
00:23:33.000 --> 00:23:37.960
You know, so Paul's been accused of bringing foreign deities into Athens.

339
00:23:38.760 --> 00:23:41.320
But he's saying he's not a tribal deity.

340
00:23:42.600 --> 00:23:47.320
He might be foreign in your thinking or in this place, but he is the God who is sovereign over

341
00:23:47.320 --> 00:23:52.360
all nations in all times and all places, including our own.

342
00:23:53.160 --> 00:23:56.360
He's guiding humanity with one purpose in view too.

343
00:23:56.920 --> 00:23:57.800
What is that?

344
00:23:57.800 --> 00:23:58.680
Verse 27.

345
00:23:59.560 --> 00:24:06.360
That they should seek God and perhaps feel their way toward Him and find Him.

346
00:24:07.480 --> 00:24:12.440
But then he says, notice this, yet He is actually not far from each one of us.

347
00:24:12.440 --> 00:24:16.200
For in Him we live and move and have our being.

348
00:24:16.920 --> 00:24:18.680
So that's the fourth thing we see about God here.

349
00:24:19.240 --> 00:24:20.520
He is near.

350
00:24:21.080 --> 00:24:22.520
He is the God who is near.

351
00:24:23.640 --> 00:24:26.200
So God is the ruler who reigns over all things.

352
00:24:26.200 --> 00:24:29.720
He's above all things, and yet He is the God who draws near.

353
00:24:31.880 --> 00:24:37.240
So the philogians describe this as that kind of tension as God's transcendence and God's

354
00:24:37.240 --> 00:24:38.360
eminence.

355
00:24:38.360 --> 00:24:41.240
Those two things are both true about God at the same time.

356
00:24:41.240 --> 00:24:48.360
So yes, He is outside and above all things, but He's also near and actively involved in our lives.

357
00:24:48.920 --> 00:24:54.840
So you see this described, for example, in Isaiah 57, verse 15 in the Old Testament.

358
00:24:54.840 --> 00:25:01.480
It says, Thus says the one who is high and lifted up, who inhabits eternity, whose name is holy.

359
00:25:01.480 --> 00:25:04.440
I dwell in the high and holy place.

360
00:25:04.440 --> 00:25:08.200
But then hear this, the God who dwells in the high and holy place.

361
00:25:09.160 --> 00:25:14.280
He says, And I also dwell with him who is of a contrite and lowly spirit.

362
00:25:15.480 --> 00:25:18.200
So His greatness and His nearness is there.

363
00:25:18.200 --> 00:25:23.640
You know, people go to great lengths to find transcendence or a sense of meanings.

364
00:25:24.280 --> 00:25:30.280
Back in the 60s or early 70s, you get the Beatles like traveling to India to find that there.

365
00:25:30.280 --> 00:25:31.240
Kind of modern day example.

366
00:25:31.240 --> 00:25:33.000
Might be that Tyler Childer is doing.

367
00:25:33.000 --> 00:25:34.360
He's done the same thing.

368
00:25:34.360 --> 00:25:35.320
Going on this pilgrimage.

369
00:25:35.320 --> 00:25:42.040
People travel all across the globe to find God or whatever is ultimately found in him.

370
00:25:43.160 --> 00:25:46.760
But the thing is, He isn't found by traveling off some distant place

371
00:25:47.640 --> 00:25:50.120
or going up to some mountain somewhere.

372
00:25:50.120 --> 00:25:53.800
He is the God who is near no matter where we are.

373
00:25:53.800 --> 00:26:01.640
And He is known by those who will humble themselves before Him as He reveals Himself in the gospel.

374
00:26:03.080 --> 00:26:04.360
Or says the God who's near.

375
00:26:05.240 --> 00:26:07.880
He's also the God who is, fifthly, Father.

376
00:26:09.320 --> 00:26:09.800
Father.

377
00:26:09.800 --> 00:26:11.160
So what does it say here?

378
00:26:11.800 --> 00:26:13.640
In Him we live and move and have our being.

379
00:26:13.720 --> 00:26:20.520
As even some of your own poets have said, for we are indeed His offspring.

380
00:26:21.320 --> 00:26:22.840
And Paul then affirms that.

381
00:26:22.840 --> 00:26:24.840
The poets said that we are His offspring.

382
00:26:24.840 --> 00:26:28.440
And Paul says being then God's offspring.

383
00:26:28.440 --> 00:26:29.640
So he kind of affirms that.

384
00:26:31.720 --> 00:26:34.280
So if you're listening closely, you'll think, well, hang on a second.

385
00:26:35.720 --> 00:26:37.160
Are we all children of God?

386
00:26:39.960 --> 00:26:43.320
Just to be clear, most scripture, when it speaks about being children of God,

387
00:26:43.320 --> 00:26:46.520
it talks about how we are not naturally children of God.

388
00:26:47.160 --> 00:26:50.200
You can go back to listen to the sermons from a couple of weeks ago.

389
00:26:50.200 --> 00:26:54.520
We saw from John chapter three about what it means to be born again.

390
00:26:54.520 --> 00:26:57.880
We have to be born again as children of God.

391
00:26:58.520 --> 00:27:03.160
So why does Paul affirm what's being said here about us being children of God?

392
00:27:03.160 --> 00:27:08.600
Well, he's not denying that we must personally become children of God through a new spiritual both.

393
00:27:09.640 --> 00:27:10.280
Birth rather.

394
00:27:10.760 --> 00:27:15.880
What he's doing is he's agreeing that there's a different sense in which God is the father of

395
00:27:15.880 --> 00:27:17.480
all humanity.

396
00:27:17.480 --> 00:27:20.520
So he's talking about God's fatherhood over all humanity.

397
00:27:20.520 --> 00:27:24.280
In other words, God is the one who gives life to all.

398
00:27:24.280 --> 00:27:26.760
So in that sense, he fathers humanity.

399
00:27:27.560 --> 00:27:32.760
But also all of humanity is created in his image, in his likeness.

400
00:27:32.760 --> 00:27:36.040
So in that sense, God is the father of all humanity.

401
00:27:36.440 --> 00:27:41.400
But then we know him uniquely as father when we become his children through Jesus.

402
00:27:44.040 --> 00:27:48.280
But thinking about his fatherhood in relation to humanity, and often when a baby is born,

403
00:27:48.280 --> 00:27:54.200
people will say something like, oh, he looks just like his dad, or oh, she looks just like

404
00:27:54.200 --> 00:27:56.040
her mother, or the other way around.

405
00:27:56.040 --> 00:28:00.040
But what you don't hear is people generally saying like, when the father walks in the room

406
00:28:00.040 --> 00:28:02.040
like, oh, you look just like the baby.

407
00:28:02.520 --> 00:28:06.040
That might be true, but we think of it in the other direction.

408
00:28:06.040 --> 00:28:07.640
So this is the flow of thought here.

409
00:28:07.640 --> 00:28:11.640
So this is who God is, and we are created in his likeness.

410
00:28:11.640 --> 00:28:18.200
And so it's then absurd to say that we can create a God in our likeness.

411
00:28:18.200 --> 00:28:21.400
So it's the wrong way around.

412
00:28:21.400 --> 00:28:23.000
So what does Paul say here?

413
00:28:23.000 --> 00:28:28.360
He says, being in God's offspring, we ought not to think that the divine being

414
00:28:28.360 --> 00:28:30.920
is like the father of all humanity.

415
00:28:30.920 --> 00:28:36.280
The divine being is like created things like gold, or silver, or stone, or an image formed

416
00:28:36.280 --> 00:28:39.400
by the art and imagination of man.

417
00:28:39.400 --> 00:28:42.520
So we're the ones that have been created.

418
00:28:42.520 --> 00:28:46.120
We do not create God, but sadly this is what people do.

419
00:28:46.120 --> 00:28:50.760
And that can take place in the way that Paul is directly addressing here in his

420
00:28:50.760 --> 00:28:54.760
context through created images of God that we worship.

421
00:28:54.760 --> 00:28:58.760
But the same thing can happen in how we conceive of God in our minds.

422
00:28:59.160 --> 00:29:04.360
So instead of submitting ourselves to the God who is, to the God who has revealed himself,

423
00:29:05.480 --> 00:29:10.120
we conjure up the God we want to be, the God we want to exist.

424
00:29:12.120 --> 00:29:19.240
We can create a God who is an image of how we tend to think or feel about things.

425
00:29:20.200 --> 00:29:24.200
So that's what we want God to be like, because we want him to agree with us.

426
00:29:25.160 --> 00:29:30.760
Or it can also happen to be a God who reflects whatever the cultural narrative that we are

427
00:29:30.760 --> 00:29:33.160
buying into is at the moment.

428
00:29:33.160 --> 00:29:38.520
So like wherever society is at, like well that's who God must be or what he must be like.

429
00:29:38.520 --> 00:29:42.600
So sometimes you hear people say like, well I would never believe in a God like that.

430
00:29:42.600 --> 00:29:43.720
That's not my God.

431
00:29:43.720 --> 00:29:48.760
Well the question is not like who is your God, or what do you feel like God is like,

432
00:29:48.760 --> 00:29:52.920
or how do you think about God, but who has God revealed himself to be?

433
00:29:53.880 --> 00:29:57.160
We don't get the God we want, we get the God who is.

434
00:29:58.440 --> 00:30:03.960
So many people are worshiping a, pardon me, but like a distorted Frankenstein like God,

435
00:30:04.520 --> 00:30:09.880
who's created by taking all these different things that we think and feel, be it our desires,

436
00:30:09.880 --> 00:30:13.240
or our politics, or our values.

437
00:30:13.240 --> 00:30:17.960
We put all of that together with a bit of what Scripture says about God.

438
00:30:17.960 --> 00:30:20.200
That is then what we worship.

439
00:30:21.160 --> 00:30:27.160
You know there's a unique and grievous blasphemy that's taking place in our cultural context

440
00:30:27.160 --> 00:30:29.000
that was not taking place in Athens.

441
00:30:29.880 --> 00:30:36.280
And that is why we take that God that we create in our own image and we say that is the God of the Bible.

442
00:30:37.800 --> 00:30:38.680
This is Jesus.

443
00:30:39.480 --> 00:30:41.960
We're actually just projecting ourselves.

444
00:30:43.800 --> 00:30:48.840
Worship belongs to the God who is and to him alone, not who we want him to be.

445
00:30:49.560 --> 00:30:52.120
He will not be worshiped alone, side any other.

446
00:30:52.760 --> 00:30:55.800
Sixthly, we'll just go through this briefly for the last two.

447
00:30:56.520 --> 00:30:57.880
This God is also judge.

448
00:31:00.040 --> 00:31:07.160
Verse 30 says, the times of ignorance God overlooked, but now he commands all people

449
00:31:07.160 --> 00:31:13.480
everywhere to repent because he is fixed today on which he will judge the world

450
00:31:13.480 --> 00:31:16.440
in righteousness by a man whom he has appointed.

451
00:31:17.400 --> 00:31:22.120
And of this he is given assurance to all by raising him from the dead.

452
00:31:23.160 --> 00:31:28.440
So remember Paul's audience here is judging whether or not he should be preaching this

